The public interest model litigants are expected to serve requires that they eschew technicality and pursue fairness in the conduct of proceedings: Melbourne Steamship Ltd v Moorhead (1912) 15 CLR 333 at 342; 18 ALR 533;  BC1200025  (Crown not to take a “purely technical point of pleading”); Sebel Products v Cmr of Customs and Excise [1949] Ch 409 at 413; [1949] 1 All ER 729  (Crown should not take technical defences); Kenny v South Australia (1987) 46 SASR 268 at 273  (compliance with procedural requirements); Yong Jun Qin v Minister for Immigration and Ethnic Affairs (1997) 75 FCR 155 at 166–167; 144 ALR 695;  BC9702362  (Crown not to take purely procedural point — whether minister named as a party); Scott v Handley (1999) 58 ALD 373; [1999] FCA 404;  BC9901689 at [43]–[46]  (Crown opposing adjournment application after delay in service of affidavits). Failure to comply with these general principles may be taken into account in the exercise of the costs discretion: Hawkesbury District Health Service Ltd v Chaker [2010] NSWCA 320;  BC201008876 at [178] ff (inadequate response by hospital to legitimate inquiry did not comply with obligations of a model litigant or with the requirements of CPA 
s 56
).

